## Executive Summary

Japan is a strategic UNHCR donor with a 2025 commitment of \$60.9
million, showing a strong focus on East Asia and diversified regional
support expanding from 7 to 11 countries (2022-2025). Compared to peers,
Japan stands out for earmarking 38.8% of its funding, reflecting a
preference for targeted, accountability-driven contributions. Despite
sizeable peak funding years, Japan’s overall funding pattern is marked
by high volatility and smaller, less frequent transactions—averaging
\$739,000 across 92 annually—challenging sustained program planning.
Fundraising efforts should emphasize Japan’s commitment to geographic
expansion and regional priorities, advocating for stabilized, increased,
and more predictable contributions aligned with its earmarking
preferences.

## Volatility

The analysis of UNHCR funding from Japan reveals significant funding
volatility with an average transaction amount of approximately 739,000
US dollars, conducted through around 92 transactions annually. This
contrasts sharply with the top 10 other donors, whose average
transaction amount is about 2.9 million US dollars via 371 transactions
per year, indicating that Japan’s contributions are smaller in both size
and frequency. The dataset includes 275 funding transactions spanning
from January 2023 to December 2025, with transaction values
demonstrating considerable variability, reaching a maximum near 10.9
million dollars but a median value much lower, reflecting occasional
high-value contributions against generally smaller and irregular funding
flows. This funding pattern suggests challenges for sustained planning
and operational reliability, underlining the importance of diversifying
and stabilizing funding sources. For proposal and fundraising
strategists, it is critical to address these fluctuations in funding by
advocating for increased transaction frequency and volume from Japan,
leveraging complementary donors, and designing flexible programs that
can adapt to variable cash flows. Enhancing predictability can improve
operational continuity for UNHCR activities in Japan and overall
resource optimization.
